    <h1 class="page-title">Particle acceleration (basics)</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Particle acceleration (basics)</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Type:</th><td>Concept</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Educational level:</th><td>Undergraduate</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Key Papers:</th><td>Hillas (1984); Bell (2011)</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Particle acceleration</strong> refers to processes that energize charged particles above the thermal distribution. Common mechanisms include diffusive shock acceleration (DSA), magnetic reconnection, and stochastic (turbulent) acceleration.</p>

    <h2>Basic ideas</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Energy gain</strong> — Particles gain energy by repeatedly scattering across moving magnetic irregularities or shocks.</li>
      <li><strong>Power-law spectra</strong> — DSA naturally produces power-law momentum distributions f(p) ~ p<sup>-q</sup> with q set by shock compression ratio.</li>
      <li><strong>Maximum energy</strong> — Constrained by confinement (Hillas criterion), radiative losses, and finite acceleration time.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why this matters</h2>
    <p>Understanding basic acceleration sets expectations for non-thermal emission from jets. The paper 2603.16647 applies these ideas to recollimation shocks to predict maximal particle energies for different jet classes.</p>

